text: In 1991 during the filming for 'Point Break' Keanu Reeves (whose role involved playing rookie FBI agent 'Johnny Utah') was surfing with co-stars when a small child was dragged under the waves and began to struggle to stay above surface. As his co-stars rushed to help, Reeves held out an arm infront of them, stopping them and was reported saying by Lori Petty (who played the character Tyler Endicott in the film) "The waves have claimed her, let her fight for her own life". The crew, dumbfounded, proceeded to watch her struggle until her body disappeared beneath the waves, lifeless. He was later spotted outside the child's house, making drowning gestures and thanking the family for their child's sacrifice to the great ocean.

text: Lmao. Some of these comments... xD My opinion on the movie is this: The story-line may seem cheesy, Keanu Reeves may have a shitty name in the movie and it may look like mindless destruction driven lead-to-air slow-mo-walking-away-from-explosions madness, but I mean.. Hey... What's wrong with that? I think the point is that Directors are running out of ideas for movies, and creating some pretty dumb ones (ie: I, Frankenstein). Chad Stahelski seems like what he's trying to say is, a movie doesn't need to have a story-line that has been created over the span of 10 years that creates a vortex in the space-time continuum and literally blows minds away with it's plot twists. When most of us watch a movie involving loss, revenge, assassins and mayhem, all we really want to see is a few close combat fights involving multiple people getting there ass kicked, incredible reaction timing and accuracy, cool assassin stuff, the "Bad" guy getting beaten through impossible odds, and a lot of blood and ingenious deaths. It seems as though that is delivered in this case. Plus, Reeves is actually one of the good actors in my opinion. Not the best, but legendary nonetheless. "It's not WHAT you did, son.. It's WHO you did it to..." Btw, Kelime, "Don't kill a retired Hit-man's puppy that was a gift from his dying wife. And don't steal his car either." made me laugh my ass off. 10/10 best conclusion/review/comment of 2014. Thanks for the laugh.

text: Some say, "All of this death for a fucking dog!" and they couldn't be more wrong.   !Spoilers Ahead!  John wick was not a good man, he bathed in the blood from countless years as a hit-man working for mob bosses. Yet he was pulled from this life when he met the love of his life and his future wife . She tamed the beast beast within him and put it to sleep. Sadly this would not last, as she was taken from him due to an unknown illness. Now alone, there was nothing to keep him from falling back into the darkness from whence he came. Save Daisy a puppy, given to John as a parting gift from his late wife who knew John needed something to hold on to after she was gone. No longer alone, John had hope, he no longer had to grieve by himself, he was going to make it through this.   Now this "punk-ass-bitch" breaks into his house, steals his car (and not just any car, that ride is beyond sweet) and kills Daisy the last thing he'll receive from his late wife. With Daisy gone, there is nothing left in John but sadness and hate. The beast that had been sleeping, now awakes and there's nothing left  to restrain it.   "John will come for you and you will do nothing because you can do nothing!"

text: I'm honestly not a troll, I watched this film and thought it was genuinely, total shit!  Weak plot, (bloody stupid tbh) poor acting, cheesy dialogue, predictable/un-original revenge type shoot-em-up. No real twist. Bad, bad, bad. Like a bad Jean Claude Van Damme film!  *(Big sigh), I just had to get that out of my system. I realize that (bizarrely) I am in the small minority and EVERYBODY else LOVED the film! People saying "My most favourite film of all time!" and the film has great reviews.  I believe that I have good taste, I love "A few good men", "Snatch", "Matrix", "Terminator", "Die Hard", "Forrest Gump", "Shawshank redemption", "Goodfellas", "Silence of the lambs", "Reservoir dogs", "American beauty" etc etc. I like to watch a film and forget that I'm watching a film, I want to be captivated. I like films with unique characters, interesting dialogue, a good story, plausibility. "John Wick" Lacks all of this! The plot (Retired assassin gets burgled, his dog gets killed and so he goes on a killing spree) could've been written by a child.  Is this the "Belieber" culture I find myself living in these days. Have people got no standards or taste anymore? Are the fans of this shitty film going to become the screen writers and directors of films to come?  :(
